%% Current fragile direct HTTP call vs proposed durable message queue between ingest and indexing

flowchart TB

    subgraph DIRECT["CURRENT — Direct HTTP call  (fragile)"]
        direction LR
        I1["Ingest Service"] -- "POST /query/index" --> Q1["Query Service"]
        Q1 --> DOWN1["If Query Service is down or slow:\n✗ indexing call FAILS immediately\n✗ no retry mechanism\n✗ indexing is LOST — log never appears in search\n✗ no backpressure — burst can overwhelm query service\n✗ caller waits on network timeout"]
    end

    subgraph QUEUE_PROP["PROPOSED — Message Queue  (durable, decoupled)"]
        direction LR
        I2["Ingest Service"] -- "publish message\n(fire and forget)" --> MQ["Message Queue\nRabbitMQ or Kafka\n\nMessages persist here\nuntil consumed"]
        MQ -- "consume when ready\n(at own pace)" --> Q2["Query Service"]
        MQ --> UP1["If Query Service is down:\n✓ messages queue up safely in the broker\n✓ automatic retry with configurable backoff\n✓ dead-letter queue — failed messages captured\n  for manual inspection and replay\n✓ burst absorption — queue buffers sudden\n  spikes without overwhelming the consumer\n✓ ordering guarantees (Kafka — per partition)"]
    end

    NOTE_WHY["Why RabbitMQ vs Kafka?\nRabbitMQ — simpler, great for task queues, built-in DLQ, easier ops.\nKafka — needed when you want replay, ordering guarantees, or\nhigh-throughput event streaming with multiple consumer groups."]

    DIRECT      --> QUEUE_PROP
    QUEUE_PROP  --> NOTE_WHY
